    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_740957162" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/740957162" />
    <a title="Kavita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita"><img alt="Kavita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315387023p2/5858699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/740957162?book_show_action=true">Oct 13, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kavita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kavita" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita">Kavita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=wtf">wtf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=china">china</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=romance">romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=ghosts-and-horror">ghosts-and-horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer740957162" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17966408356309901826">This book is quite hard to classify and I cannot even decide whether I liked it or not. It could be historical fiction, but not quite. There has been excellent research on Chinese practices during the Ming dynasty, and Chinese beliefs in the afterlife have been depicted in detail. The book is basically set in the past, and is based on real people who lived and a real opera wrote in the 1500s. But most of the book is about a ghost, so historical fiction doesn’t quite fit.<br/><br/>Then this could be classi</span>
  <span id="freeText17966408356309901826" style="display:none">This book is quite hard to classify and I cannot even decide whether I liked it or not. It could be historical fiction, but not quite. There has been excellent research on Chinese practices during the Ming dynasty, and Chinese beliefs in the afterlife have been depicted in detail. The book is basically set in the past, and is based on real people who lived and a real opera wrote in the 1500s. But most of the book is about a ghost, so historical fiction doesn’t quite fit.<br /><br />Then this could be classified as feminist fiction, but not quite. To be sure, there are many feminist lessons to be learned from this book. Peony has led a cloistered life in an attempt by her parents to protect her but in the end, women cannot be ‘protected’ by others. They can only be taught to live life and defend themselves as best as they can. The book also deals with women’s education, which is often not considered as important as a man’s, even today. Women poets in China have existed for centuries but they have not been honoured in the same way as men poets. This is an important theme that the book focuses on. And finally, the danger of keeping your daughter away from any man in the hopes of selling her off in an arranged marriage is explored in detail. (Any book that shows arranged marriages as inhuman social constructions gets an extra star.) But then again, there are very unfeminist elements in the book such as Peony desiring both her husband’s and her parents’ families to have sons to carry on the lineage. Peony and her sister-wife-ghost also fight over Ren as if they were stupid teenagers. It was all about a man, and not about women’s desires. As a ghost, Peony could have been depicted as rising above petty traditions that discriminate against women, but she doesn’t. She remains a woman who strongly believes in female inferiority even as a ghost, when she is supposed to have been released from all earthly obligations. Also, everyone keeps sneering about Peony being a worthless branch of the family tree for the sole reason that she was female. So no, I cannot accept this as feminist fiction. <br /><br />And finally, it could be a love story. But considering that the main characters only meet each other THREE times, I can hardly consider it one. Besides, one character is dead for most of the book and they NEVER meet again.<br /><br />Basically, this book is about a girl who has absolutely no idea about life and no one would tell her anything about it either. She meets a man ONCE by mistake, and then falls in ‘love’. Errr ... okay! Then she starves herself to death over him, and her family throws her out to die because she must not die within the house since she is an unmarried woman. Whatever! And then begins the REAL weird part as Peony becomes a ghost and starts haunting her to-be husband, who marries another woman. She haunts the other wife and so on until she dies. And then she mothers a child by proxy and breaks her feet and gets her married off to Ren (WTF!) and then claims she has found motherly love with her sister wife! Gimme a break! And then, when evil second wife returns to harm innocent third wife, all hell breaks loose. And then, she is finally released when her husband takes care of the last rite. There is simply no point to the story once she becomes a ghost. And I certainly did not need to read about a ghost woman joining in the copulation between husband and wife and ... I just have no words. <br /><br />On the other hand, I enjoyed reading the book even though I was fuming most of the time over Peony’s stupidity. It’s just one of those books. 3 stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17966408356309901826" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


