    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2141872450" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2141872450" />
    <a title="Kim A" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70241549-kim-a"><img alt="Kim A" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1515702928p2/70241549.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2141872450?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kim A" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kim A" href="/user/show/70241549-kim-a">Kim A</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70241549-kim-a?shelf=2017-faves">2017-faves</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2141872450" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10184132422062058382"><u>Sections of the book I found both beautiful and sad.</u><br/><br/><b>&quot;I was adamant that my poems not be found, but I didn&apos;t have the strength of will to set fire to them. Too many women burn their words in a fit of thinking them not worthy, only to regret it later&quot;.<br/><br/>&quot;When a girl falls into marriage, she exhales her beauty, and loses forever her romantic image. She still has many obligations to fulfill-giving birth to sons, honoring her husband&apos;s ancestors, becoming a chaste widow-but she has already begun her gl</b></span>
  <span id="freeText10184132422062058382" style="display:none"><u>Sections of the book I found both beautiful and sad.</u><br /><br /><b>"I was adamant that my poems not be found, but I didn't have the strength of will to set fire to them. Too many women burn their words in a fit of thinking them not worthy, only to regret it later".<br /><br />"When a girl falls into marriage, she exhales her beauty, and loses forever her romantic image. She still has many obligations to fulfill-giving birth to sons, honoring her husband's ancestors, becoming a chaste widow-but she has already begun her glide into death"</b><br /><br />Once again another Lisa See novel I just loved. While it took me a bit to get into the "after life" section of the book, I was glad I did as that's where the rewards were. In the end it wasn't as much the plot of the book but rather the sub plot and the linking of the main female characters. All had voices and wanted to be heard in a society that told them their opinions were useless and unwelcome.<br /><br />A wonderful read and really appreciated See's author's notes at the end where she writes about the extensive research she did while preparing for and writing this book</span>
  <a data-text-id="10184132422062058382" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


